EBERE CHIBUZOR The Director-General of the National Council for Arts and Culture (NCAC), Otunba Segun Runsewe has pledged commitment to partner with the National Youths Service Corps, NYSC, in working towards achieving sustainable peace across the States. Runsewe made this known when he received the Director-General (NYSC), Brigadier-General, Shuaibu Ibrahim in his office. While unveiling a joint agenda tagged “Partnership That Works”, Runsewe said that NCAC and NYSC have a similar mandate. READ ALSO: Uphold African culture to curb sexual violence, rape — NCAC He noted that while the NYSC was established in 1973 by Gen. Gowon administration in pursuance of the policy of Reconciliation, Reconstruction and Rehabilitation, the National Festival for Art and Culture was established by the same regime to foster national peace, unity and integration using culture. Otunba Runsewe further said that while NYSC scheme brings together young Nigerians to serve in States other than their own, NAFEST brings together contingents from the 36 States and FCT to showcase their cultural peculiarities and exchange cultural ideas. Runsewe appealed to all organisations to always accept corp members posted to them and treat with respect as they are in the service to the nation. The Director-General, Brigadier-General Shuaibu Ibrahim thanked his counterpart in the Arts and Culture for accepting to partner with NYSC which Runsewe described as the partnership that works. On the issue of the spread of Covid-19 in the NYSC camps, the DG, NYSC explained that all prospective corp members are screened and tested before being allowed into the camp. He added that NCDC has it is their offices in all the orientation camps in the country to take care of any emergency that may occur.